	<Title>
		Recipe: Watermelon-cranberry agua fresca
	</Title>
	<Abstract>
		Watermelon-cranberry agua fresca &amp;mdash; one of many healthy recipes from Mayo Clinic.
	</Abstract>
	<ServingInfo Label="Serves">
		6
	</ServingInfo>
	<DietitianTip Label="Dietitian&apos;s tip">
		&lt;p&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Dietitian&apos;s tip:&lt;/strong&gt; Aguas frescas are popular fresh-fruit drinks in Mexico. Although water is a standard ingredient, this undiluted version is a thirst-quenching refresher whether accompanying spicy foods or sipped in the sun.
&lt;/p&gt;
	</DietitianTip>
	<Directions Label="Directions">
		&lt;p&gt;
Place the melon in a blender or food processor. Process until smooth. Pass the puree through a fine-mesh sieve placed over a bowl to eliminate the pulp and clarify the juice. Pour the juice into a large pitcher. Add the cranberry and lime juices and stir to combine. Refrigerate until very cold. Pour into tall chilled glasses and garnish each with a fresh lime slice. 
&lt;/p&gt;
	</Directions>
	<Ingredients Label="Ingredients">
		&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;2 1/2 pounds seedless watermelon, rind removed and diced (about 7 cups)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;1 cup fruit-sweetened cranberry juice (sometimes called cranberry nectar)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;1/4 cup fresh lime juice&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;1 lime, cut into 6 slices&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
	</Ingredients>
